                <a name="id2450692" id=
                "id2450692">Requirements===





There are no known minimum system requirements for
          running tovid. If your machine is capable of running a
          standard Linux installation, then you probably have
          enough CPU power for video processing and playback.


If you're going to work with video files, you probably
          want to have plenty of hard drive space to spare; the
          process of authoring a DVD might consume 11GB on your
          disk, and if you are working on several DVD projects at
          once, the space requirements multiply quickly. At
          minimum, you should have about 20GB that you can devote
          to authoring DVDs. If you only plan to create (S)VCDs,
          you could get by with only 6-8GB.


The tovid suite is developed and tested primarily on
          Linux. Some users have also reported successful execution
          on FreeBSD and Cygwin with only minor modifications.
          Parts of the suite may work on other UNIX-like operating
          systems, but that possibility is unverified at this
          point. There are currently no plans to develop a Windows
          or Mac OS port, but if you are interested in taking on
          the job, please contact the tovid developers!


Several software packages are required in order to use
          various components of the tovid suite (see <a href=
          "#sec:Dependencies" title=
          "Dependencies">Dependencies). Nearly all of the
          components, being written in the <strong class=
          "command">bash** scripting language,
          require <strong class=
          "command">bash**, as well as standard UNIX
          utilities like <strong class=
          "command">grep**, <strong class=
          "command">sed**, <strong class=
          "command">cat**, and <strong class=
          "command">awk**. If you are running Linux,
          all of these should already be available.






                <a name="sec:Dependencies" id=
                "sec:Dependencies">Dependencies===





tovid has amassed some dependency hell during its
          development. Here is the complete list of dependencies,
          and to what extent they are required:



              : <span class=
              "application"><a href="http://www.python.org/"
              target="_top">Python




An interpreter that allows you to run programs
                written in Python. Python is becoming increasingly
                common, so it's good to have a Python interpreter
                installed. If you want to use the graphical
                interface for tovid, you need this.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href="http://www.wxpython.org/"
              target="_top">wxPython




Provides support for <span class=
                "acronym">GUIs written in Python using the
                wxWidgets API. You
                also need this to run the GUI.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href="http://www.mplayerhq.hu/"
              target="_top">mplayer




Probably the most robust and mature video player
                for Linux. Almost all of the tovid components
                depend heavily on mplayer for video playback and
                conversion, so this is a must-install. You'll want
                mplayer anyway, if you plan to be working with
                video.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href="http://mjpeg.sourceforge.net/"
              target="_top">mjpegtools




Command-line tools for encoding and working with
                video, particularly MPEG. This is required by most
                of tovid's components, and you will need it in
                order to do anything useful with tovid.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href=
              "http://ffmpeg.sourceforge.net/" target=
              "_top">ffmpeg




Tools and libraries for recording, converting,
                and streaming audio and video. Used by several
                components, and required if you want to create DVDs
                in <em class=
                "glossterm">NTSC format.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href="http://www.imagemagick.org"
              target="_top">ImageMagick




A powerful set of command-line tools for
                formatting, resizing, converting and drawing on
                image files. This is used by the
                <a href="#makemenu"
                title="makemenu">makemenu**, the
                menu-generation component of tovid. If you want to
                create video discs with menus, you need this. Many
                Linux distributions install this by default.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href="http://sox.sourceforge.net/"
              target="_top">SoX




The ImageMagick of audio processing, in a way.
                Command-line tools for converting, trimming, and
                filtering audio files. This is used by
                <a href="#makemenu"
                title="makemenu">makemenu**.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href=
              "http://dvdauthor.sourceforge.net/" target=
              "_top">dvdauthor 0.6.0 or
              newer




Tools for creating DVD filesystems. If you want
                to make DVDs with tovid, you need this.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href="http://www.vcdimager.org/"
              target="_top">vcdimager




Tools for creating (S)VCD filesystems. If you
                want to make VCDs or SVCDs, you need this.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href=
              "http://zebra.fh-weingarten-de/~transcode/" target=
              "_top">transcode




Video stream processing and conversion tools.
                This is used by postproc (the tovid postprocessing
                component) and <strong class=
                "command"><a href="#dvrequant" title=
                "dvrequant">dvrequant** (the
                tovid DVD shrinking tool). Useful if you want to be
                able to fine-tune the output size of your videos,
                to fit a desired amount of content on a recordable
                DVD.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href=
              "http://developers.videolan.org/libdvdcss/" target=
              "_top">libdvdcss




DVD decryption routines, used for playing
                encrypted DVDs on your computer. Needed by
                <a href="#dvrequant"
                title="dvrequant">dvrequant** for
                copying encrypted DVDs. You want this.


              : <span class=
              "application"><a href=
              "http://untrepid.com/acidrip/lsdvd.html" target=
              "_top">lsdvd




Handy tool for viewing the attributes of DVD
                discs. Also needed by <strong class=
                "command"><a href="#dvrequant" title=
                "dvrequant">dvrequant**, for
                copying discs.







Most of these tools are widely available in major
          package repositories; chances are good that you can get
          them all through your distribution's preferred package
          manager.







