You can get a copy of the latest development version
          of tovid through CVS. To get this version, you need to
          have <a href="http://www.cvshome.org/" target=
          "_top">CVS installed.


Using CVS is a little different; instead of just
          downloading tovid, you'll be "checking out" a copy of it.
          Using the same example directory as above:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``cd ~/Downloads``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``cvs -d:pserver:anonymous@cvs.sourceforge.net:/cvsroot/tovid login``**
<code class=
"computeroutput">Logging in to :pserver:anonymous@cvs.sourceforge.net:2401/cvsroot/tovid``
CVS password:`` <strong class=
"userinput">``(your email address)``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``cvs -d:pserver:anonymous@cvs.sourceforge.net:/cvsroot/tovid co -P tovid``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``cvs -d:pserver:anonymous@cvs.sourceforge.net:/cvsroot/tovid co -P gui``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``cd tovid``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``aclocal``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``autoconf``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``automake``**

```



If you're installing the GUI, repeat these steps in
          its directory (<strong class=
          "command">aclocal**, <strong class=
          "command">autoconf**, and
          automake**).
          Finally, do <strong class=
          "command">./configure** and
          su -c "make
          install"** as shown above in each
          repsective directory to install tovid (and the GUI)
          system-wide.

