This chapter gives an overview of how to use the
      command-line tools; see the <a href="#manpages" title=
      "tovid suite manual pages">manpages for more detailed
      usage notes.


If using the command line does not sound like your cup of
      tea, you may choose the tovid GUI instead. The GUI makes the
      disc authoring process much simpler and more interactive. See
      [Using the GUI #gui].





              <a name=
              "id2496992" id="id2496992">The scripts==





tovid's foundation
        rests on a collection of shell scripts designed for
        specific tasks relevant to authoring a video disc. One
        script converts video, another makes menus, another
        generates the disc navigation structure, etc. Here's how it
        all fits together:





**Figure&nbsp;1.&nbsp;Organization of
          the tools**


            <img src="images/tovid_cli_organization.jpg" alt=
            "Organization of the tools">




The blue gear icons are the primary tovid scripts. Each
        script has certain inputs and outputs; for example, the
        <a href="#tovid" title=
        "tovid">tovid** script takes any
        multimedia video file as input, and produces (S)VCD or
        DVD-compliant MPEG video files as output. The output of
        <a href="#tovid" title=
        "tovid">tovid** then becomes an input to
        makevcd** or
        <a href="#makedvd" title=
        "makedvd">makedvd**, and so on.


tovid follows the UNIX tradition of modularization.
        Rather than having a single large program that does
        everything, tovid has several smaller programs that do
        specific things:



            - 

<a href="#tovid"
              title="tovid">tovid** converts
              arbitrary multimedia video files to (S)VCD, DVD, or
              KVCD-compliant format.


            - 

<a href="#makemenu"
              title="makemenu">makemenu** create
              an MPEG menu, for navigating a video disc.


            - 

<a href="#makexml"
              title="makexml">makexml** generates
              an XML description of video disc content, compatible
              with <strong class=
              "command">vcdxbuild** or
              <strong class=
              "command">dvdauthor**.


            - 

<a href="#makedvd"
              title="makedvd">makedvd** authors
              and optionally burns a DVD.


            - 

<strong class=
              "command">makevcd** authors and
              optionally burns a VCD or SVCD (not yet complete)










                <a name="id2497157" id=
                "id2497157">Five steps===





Creating a video disc using the command-line tools
          boils down to five steps:



              - 

Plan
                ahead. Decide what videos you would
                like to include on the disc, and whether you want
                to make an (S)VCD or a DVD. If you have lots of
                videos, you may want to have navigational menus to
                select them for playback. Sketch out an outline of
                what menus you want to have, and what videos they
                will link to.


              - 

Encode the
                content. Almost all video sources need
                to be converted to an (S)VCD or DVD-compliant
                format. The <a href=
                "#tovid" title="tovid">tovid**
                script does this for you; use it to convert all the
                videos you want to include. You can use
                <strong class=
                "command">tovid-batch** to convert
                several videos at once.


              - 

Create menus
                (optional). If you want your disc to
                have interactive menus for navigation, use
                <a href="#makemenu"
                title="makemenu">makemenu** to
                create them. This is where you will specify video
                titles, as they will appear on the menu.


              - 

Layout the
                disc. This is where you specify exactly
                how your disc will be organized. Provide the names
                of all your video and menu files, and
                <a href="#makexml"
                title="makexml">makexml** does
                the rest.


              - 

Author and
                burn. When you reach this step, you
                should have several <code class=
                "filename">.mpg`` files (menus and videos),
                along with a .xml``
                file containing the disc layout. Give the
                .xml`` file to
                <strong class=
                "command">makevcd** or
                <a href="#makedvd"
                title="makedvd">makedvd** to
                author and burn your disc.







For a step-by-step example of creating a disc, see the
          [tovid howto #howto].






                <a name="id2497314" id=
                "id2497314">Other scripts===





There are several additional scripts customized for
          other tasks:



              - 

<a href=
                "#dvrequant" title=
                "dvrequant">dvrequant** copies a
                single track, with optional subtitles and multiple
                audio streams, from an existing DVD.


              - 

<a href="#idvid"
                title="idvid">idvid** identifies
                video files, telling you the duration, resolution,
                codec, and other useful information. Perhaps most
                important, it can tell you whether a given video
                file is compliant with (S)VCD or DVD.


              - 

<strong class=
                "command">makeslides** creates a
                still-image slideshow, in (S)VCD format, from
                arbitrary images. Slideshows may be included on a
                disc using the -slides``
                option to <a href=
                "#makexml" title=
                "makexml">makexml**.


              - 

<strong class=
                "command">postproc** does
                post-processing on an encoded/compliant MPEG video.
                It can shrink the video stream by reducing quality,
                and it can adjust the audio/video
                synchronization.


              - 

<strong class=
                "command">tovid-batch** processes
                multiple video files using the same output options.
                Use this if you want to encode several videos to
                the same format.


              - 

<strong class=
                "command">tovid-interactive** is an
                interactive command-line tool that prompts you for
                all the necessary <strong class=
                "command"><a href="#tovid" title=
                "tovid">tovid** encoding options.
                Use this if you are unfamiliar with the command
                line, but do not want to run the GUI for whatever
                reason.







Each of these is described in more detail in the
          sections that follow.







              <a name=
              "cli.config" id="cli.config">Configuration
              files==





The version-0.18 <a href=
        "#tovid" title="tovid">tovid** script
        implements the use of configuration files. Eventually, all
        the major tovid scripts will be able to read configuration
        files from a global directory, a user-preference directory,
        and from a supplied text file.


Configuration files for the tovid suite are plain ASCII
        text. The first line of the file begins with a script name
        (such as <strong class=
        "command">tovid**, <strong class=
        "command">makexml**, or <strong class=
        "command">makemenu**); the remainder of the
        file consists of command-line options appropriate to that
        script. Whitespace is ignored, and comments may be included
        on lines beginning with #``.

tovid
# sample tovid configuration file

# This is a comment, and will be ignored by tovid

# Always use NTSC format by default
-ntsc

# Run in "parallel" mode for faster execution and
# reduced disk usage
-parallel

# Run in "debug" mode, so when something goes wrong
# it's easier to diagnose
-debug

# Always overwrite existing output files.
-overwrite

```



This format makes editing a snap, especially if you are
        already familiar with tovid's various command-line options.
        You may find configuration files useful, if you get tired
        of entering the same options by hand for a bunch of videos,
        or if you want to customize your bitrates, menus, or
        formats for a certain project.


<a href="#gui" title=
        "Using the GUI">tovidgui.py** will
        someday be able to save and load projects. The save-file
        format will again be plain ASCII text, and will look like
        several configuration files concatenated
        together&ndash;some for <strong class=
        "command"><a href="#tovid" title=
        "tovid">tovid**, some for
        <a href="#makexml" title=
        "makexml">makexml**, and some for
        <a href="#makemenu" title=
        "makemenu">makemenu**.


