              target="_top">Metal Gear Solid 4











              <a name=
              "id2497733" id="id2497733">Converting the
              videos==





Videos come in all kinds of formats, but <a href=
        "#DVD">DVD only accepts a
        few specific standard formats. Fortunately, you don't have
        to worry much about it, because the <strong class=
        "command"><a href="#tovid" title=
        "tovid">tovid** script does all the
        conversion for you. You tell it what video you want to
        encode (the -in`` option), and
        what name you want for the output file (the <code class=
        "option">-out`` option). For example:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``tovid -in MGS4.wmv -out Metal_Gear_Solid_4``**

```



This will convert MGS4.wmv``
        to [NTSC #NTSC] DVD
        format, saving the result as <code class=
        "filename">Metal_Gear_Solid_4.mpg``. Since this is the
        output format I want to use, all I have to do is run the
        above command on each of my videos:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``tovid -in Serenity.mpg -out Serenity_trailer``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``tovid -in HHGG.mpg -out Hitchhikers_Guide``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``tovid -in ROTB.mpg -out Revenge_of_the_Brick``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``tovid -in MGS4.mpg -out Metal_Gear_Solid_4``**

```


        <div class="note" style=
        "margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;">

            Note



You can customize your output video with additional
          options, for example:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``tovid -pal -half-dvd -in MGS4.wmv -out Metal_Gear_Solid_4``**

```



This will convert to <em class=
          "glossterm">PAL format, using a "half-sized" DVD
          resolution (352x480). There are many other options for
          further customizing your output video; see the
          <a href="#tovid" title=
          "tovid">tovid** documentation, or run
          tovid -help**
          to see a complete list of them.



After running a tovid command, it's time to get that cup
        of coffee. Video encoding takes a long time! But if all
        goes well, I'll end up with four output videos:
        Serenity_trailer.mpg``,
        Hitchhikers_Guide.mpg`` and so
        on.






              <a name=
              "id2497929" id="id2497929">Creating the menu==





Next, I'd like to create a navigational menu, so that
        when I play the DVD, I can choose which video to play. DVD
        menus are themselves videos, but they have some extra stuff
        that makes them behave like menus. But again, you don't
        need to worry about all the details; just use the
        <a href="#makemenu" title=
        "makemenu">makemenu** script:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``makemenu "Serenity trailer" \
           "Hitchhiker's Guide trailer" \
           "Revenge of the Brick" \
           "Metal Gear Solid 4 trailer" \
           MiscTrailers``**

```


        <div class="note" style=
        "margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;">

            Note



The backslash at the end of each line indicates
          continuation on the next line; you can enter this command
          exactly as it appears, with backslashes, or you can enter
          it all on a single line, without backslashes.



I specify the four titles I want on the menu by
        enclosing them each in double-quotes, separated by spaces.
        The last thing is the name I want to use for the menu
        itself. When this command is done, I should have a video
        file called <code class=
        "filename">MiscTrailers.mpg``.





**Figure 1. What the menu looks
          like**


            <img src="images/howto_menu_screenshot.jpg" alt=
            "What the menu looks like">




When it's eventually authored as a DVD menu, it will
        have a yellow highlight that can be used to select a
        title.






              <a name=
              "id2498017" id="id2498017">Defining the
              structure==





The next step is to define how the DVD will be
        structured. The popular <a href=
        "http://dvdauthor.sourceforge.net/" target=
        "_top">dvdauthor tool can create a DVD file structure
        based on an XML input file in a predetermined format. But
        guess what! You don't need to worry about this format
        either, because the <a href=
        "#makexml" title="makexml">makexml**
        script can create it for you. All you need to provide is
        the filenames of your menus and videos, along with a few
        other options.


I'm using a pretty simple structure: a single menu, with
        four video titles. Here's the command I would run:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``makexml \
    -menu MiscTrailers.mpg \
        Serenity_trailer.mpg \
        Hitchhikers_Guide.mpg \
        Revenge_of_the_Brick.mpg \
        Metal_Gear_Solid_4.mpg \
    TrailerDisc``**

```



As you might have guessed, the first filename after
        -menu`` is the video containing
        the menu itself. All the filenames after that are the
        videos that are linked from that menu, in the same order
        that they are listed in the menu. Finally, the last thing
        is the name to use for output. When this command finishes,
        I'll have TrailerDisc.xml``
        containing a valid <strong class=
        "command">dvdauthor** disc structure.






              <a name=
              "id2498098" id="id2498098">Authoring and
              burning==





The <a href="#makedvd"
        title="makedvd">makedvd** script
        automates much of the process of authoring and burning the
        disc from the XML file created above. All that remains to
        do is:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``makedvd -burn TrailerDisc.xml``**

```



You can leave out the -burn``
        option, if you'd like to just author the disc and create an
        ISO image. Then, you can run the same command again with
        -burn`` to burn the
        already-created ISO.







