              <a name=
              "id2500664" id="id2500664">Comparing command-line
              options==





Debugging one day, I wanted to find out <span class=
        "emphasis">exactly what different encoding
        options are affected by the <code class=
        "option">-deinterlace`` option. The
        <a href="#tovid" title=
        "tovid">tovid** script is so complex now
        that even I can't remember all the random options that need
        to be passed to <strong class=
        "command">mpeg2enc**, <strong class=
        "command">mplayer**, and other programs upon
        which tovid depends.


So here's a quick bash script that shows you the
        difference, in detail, between two of tovid's command-line
        options.

#!/bin/bash
tovid -debug -deinterlace dv1.avi dv1_deint > 1.log
tovid -debug dv1.avi dv1_blahblah > 2.log
diff 1.log 2.log

```







              <a name=
              "id2500720" id="id2500720">Comparing videos==





It's often hard to compare the quality of two videos
        simply by watching them. The human eye is very forgiving
        when it comes to video, and it's useful to do a
        frame-by-frame comparison.


To get a dump of every frame in VIDEO, use the following
        command:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``mplayer -nosound -vo png VIDEO``**

```



If you want to see the difference between two images
        (IMAGE_1 and IMAGE_2), use one of these commands:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``convert IMAGE_1 IMAGE_2 -compose difference -composite x: &``**
$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``convert IMAGE_1 IMAGE_2 -compose difference -composite -normalize x: &``**

```



These commands use <a href="http://www.imagemagick.org/"
        target="_top">ImageMagick to display a grayscale
        representation of the difference between IMAGE_1 and
        IMAGE_2, with lighter areas indicating greater difference.
        The -normalize`` option is useful
        for images that are very similar. Use this to get a quick
        visualization of image quality, in particular the
        degredation and artifacts that are often introduced during
        conversion to another image format.


Newer versions of ImageMagick include the
        compare**
        utility. Try:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``compare IMAGE_1 IMAGE_2 x: &``**

```



If you like numbers, you might enjoy:

$`` <strong class=
"userinput">``compare -metric MAE IMAGE_1 IMAGE_2 null:``**

```



Try the metrics MSE, PSE, PSNR, and RMSE for different
        comparison types. For more on comparing images, see
        <a href="http://www.cit.gu.edu.au/~anthony/info/graphics/image_comparing"
        target="_top">Anthony Thyssen's notes on the
        subject.






