              <a name=
              "id2501063" id="id2501063">What is aspect
              ratio?==





In video processing, the <span class=
        "emphasis">aspect ratio is a pair of
        numbers that expresses the "wideness" of an image or video.
        The two numbers are a width-to-height ratio. For example,
        an aspect ratio of 4:3`` means
        the picture is 4 units wide for every 3 units in
        height.





**Figure&nbsp;B.1.&nbsp;What 4:3
          means**


            [images/4_3_grid.jpg]




Typical 1980s-1990s TV sets have this aspect ratio, as
        do most computer monitors. In the early 2000s, <a href=
        "#HDTV">High-definition TV
        (HDTV) screens have become more popular and affordable;
        HDTVs commonly have a 16:9 aspect ratio.





**Figure&nbsp;B.2.&nbsp;A 16:9
          picture**


            [images/16_9_grid.jpg]




To find the aspect ratio of a video or image, just
        measure its width and height. The aspect ratio can then be
        expressed as width:height``. If
        the picture is 24cm wide and 18cm tall, the aspect ratio
        can be expressed 24:18``.

        <div class="note" style=
        "margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;">

            Note



The aspect ratio is expressed in terms of the
          intended display
          dimensions. The resolution of an image in
          pixels is not always a good indicator of aspect ratio.
          For more on why this is so, see <a href=
          "http://www.mir.com/DMG/aspect.html" target="_top">Aspect
          Ratios and Frame Sizes.



How does 24:18`` compare to
        other aspect ratios? Is wider or narrower than other aspect
        ratios like 16:9`` or
        4:3``? It's hard to tell at a
        glance, because the denominators are different. The easiest
        way to compare aspect ratios is to reduce them to lowest
        terms by doing a simple division:

24 / 18 = 1.33
 4 /  3 = 1.33
16 /  9 = 1.78

```



The first two aspect ratios are equivalent to
        1.33:1``. Both are narrower than
        the widescreen aspect ratio of <code class=
        "literal">1.78:1``. Reducing aspect ratios to their
        lowest terms makes comparison easier.





**Figure B.3. Visual comparison of
          aspect ratios**


            <img src="images/Aspect_ratios.png" alt=
            "Visual comparison of aspect ratios">




Two other aspect ratios are commonly used in filming
        movies: 1.85:1`` (Academy
        Standard, or "flat"), and <code class=
        "literal">2.35:1`` (or "Scope", also called Panavision
        or CinemaScope). Both are even wider than <code class=
        "literal">16:9``, with Scope being almost twice as
        wide as 4:3``. The term
        "widescreen" typically refers to any aspect ratio greater
        than about 1.33:1``.


If you'd like to learn more about aspect ratios, check
        out <a href=
        "http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aspect_ratio_(image)"
        target="_top">the Wikipedia entry on the subject.






              <a name=
              "id2501290" id="id2501290">Converting between
              aspect ratios==





Since the 1950s, theatrical releases have typically used
        a widescreen aspect ratio. Most TV sets use a <code class=
        "literal">4:3`` aspect ratio, so widescreen movies
        must be converted for viewing on <code class=
        "literal">4:3`` TVs. Two popular approaches to this
        conversion are described here. They are <a href=
        "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pan_and_scan" target=
        "_top">pan and scan and <a href=
        "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Letterbox" target=
        "_top">letterbox.


With pan and scan, a 4:3``
        region is shown, cutting off the left and/or right sides of
        the original picture. A human operator (sometimes the
        director) selects areas that are important to the scene,
        and tries to fit them in the <code class=
        "literal">4:3`` frame. When the action moves to a
        different part of the screen, the visible region is panned
        over to it.





**Figure&nbsp;B.4.&nbsp;Pan and scan
          version of a widescreen film**


            <img src="images/pan_and_scan.jpg" alt=
            "Pan and scan version of a widescreen film">




Throughout the 1980s, pan and scan was by far the most
        popular home video format. Pan and scan transfers make full
        use of the 4:3`` frame, so the
        viewer's TV screen is filled at all times. In the 1980s,
        VHS still ruled the home market; pan and scan makes full
        use of VHS's low (by today's standards) resolution. By
        "zooming in" on the picture, detail and picture quality are
        better preserved.


But this gain comes at a significant loss; up to half of
        the original movie picture may be cut off. Camera shots
        framed for widescreen may look amateurish and asymmetrical
        when converted to pan and scan; sometimes, important
        characters, objects, or scenery may be lost. Some directors
        forbid pan-and-scan transfers of their films.

        <div class="note" style=
        "margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;">

            Note



Laserdisc was a popular niche market for movie buffs
          throughout VHS's reign; the picture quality of Laserdisc
          transfers is superior to that of VHS, but inferior to
          that of our beloved DVD.


See <a href="http://www.widescreen.org/examples.shtml"
          target="_top">Widescreen vs. Pan & Scan Examples
          for some comparisons of widescreen and pan and scan on
          actual movies.



The letterbox format, in contrast, preserves the entire
        width of the original picture. Since the original film is
        not as tall (relatively speaking) as a <code class=
        "literal">4:3`` TV set, the areas above and below the
        picture are filled with black.





**Figure&nbsp;B.5.&nbsp;Letterbox
          version of a widescreen film**


            <img src="images/letterbox.jpg" alt=
            "Letterbox version of a widescreen film">




The advantage of letterbox format is that all of the
        original picture is visible. The disadvantage is that it's
        shrunk down to fit a 4:3`` TV
        screen; a significant portion of the screen is "wasted" on
        the black bars. With VHS, a letterbox film would lose much
        of its original detail.


Since the late 1990s, pan and scan has become less
        popular. Its primary advantage to the consumer was optimal
        use of TV screen area, but the growing popularity of DVD,
        combined with the decreasing cost of <a href=
        "#HDTV">HDTV, has made it
        easier than ever to enjoy high-quality widescreen at home.
        By the early 2000s, sales of widescreen (letterbox) and
        full-screen (pan and scan) DVDs were almost equal; some TV
        series have even begun using <code class=
        "literal">16:9``.


There are several other approaches to creating
        4:3`` versions of films, but
        those typically require special filming techniques, or
        access to final proofs of the original film. For more
        information on video-transfer methods, see <a href=
        "http://www.digieffects.com/frames/transferfilmtovideo/filmtovideo.html"
        target="_top">How Film is Transferred to Video.






              <a name=
              "id2501495" id="id2501495">Pixels and aspect
              ratio==





Images and videos stored on a computer are saved as a
        big rectangle full of tiny square <a href=
        "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel" target=
        "_top">pixels. Each pixel stores a single color; you
        can think of a digital image as a giant paint-by-number
        grid, with millions of possible colors. The more pixels in
        a digital image, the more detail can be captured. In the
        digital camera market, this resolution is simply expressed
        in megapixels, or
        millions of pixels. A 4.0 megapixel (4 million pixel)
        camera can capture an image roughly 2,000 pixels wide and
        2,000 pixels high. It's a good thing computers are fast,
        because it would take a human a very long time to do a
        paint-by-number this big.


Digital video stored on a computer has no particular
        limitation on resolution, but digital video disc formats
        such as [VCD #VCD],
        [SVCD #SVCD], and
        [DVD #DVD] only
        allow certain resolutions, in terms of pixels. The most
        common resolution for commercial DVDs is Full-D1, which is
        720&times;480`` pixels in
        size.

        <div class="note" style=
        "margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;">

            Note



Full-D1 is actually the name of two different
          resolutions, depending on whether the DVD is formatted
          for [NTSC #NTSC]
          or [PAL #PAL]
          viewers and players. PAL uses a resolution of
          720&times;576`` for Full-D1;
          NTSC uses 720&times;480``.


In addition to Full-D1, DVD supports several other
          output resolutions, including <code class=
          "literal">352&times;480`` (<code class=
          "literal">352&times;576 PAL``) and <code class=
          "literal">352&times;240`` (<code class=
          "literal">352&times;288 PAL``). Higher resolutions
          give better detail and overall quality, but fill up more
          space on the disc. These additional resolutions allow
          even single-layer DVDs to contain from 2 to 10 hours of
          video, giving DVD authors several options for balancing
          quality with quantity.



You may notice, if you try to calculate what aspect
        ratio this is, that 720 / 480 =
        1.5``, which is not a standard aspect ratio for either
        standard or widescreen TV sets. Obviously, the resolution
        of a video in pixels
        has little bearing on the aspect ratio of the video;
        1.5:1`` is the ratio of width to
        height in pixels, but nobody watches DVDs on a <code class=
        "literal">1.5:1`` TV set.


So why the weird ratio? There's a good reason for it.
        DVD was designed to perform well with both <code class=
        "literal">1.33:1`` (4:3``
        television) and 1.78:1``
        (16:9)`` widescreen). But
        instead of having two different <span class=
        "emphasis">pixel resolutions, DVD uses only
        720&times;480``. Since
        1.5:1`` is about halfway between
        1.33:1`` and <code class=
        "literal">1.78:1``, Full-D1 DVD is well-suited to
        encoding both of these common aspect ratios.


To achieve this, videos are first squished or stretched
        to fit into 720&times;480``
        pixels. Each video is marked with a bit of information
        telling the DVD player whether <code class=
        "literal">4:3`` or 16:9``
        should be used for playback. The DVD player then
        automatically does the appropriate squishing or stretching
        to restore the proportions to normal.





**Figure&nbsp;B.6.&nbsp;Full-D1
          encoding of 4:3 aspect ratio**


            <img src="images/4_3_dvd.jpg" alt=
            "Full-D1 encoding of 4:3 aspect ratio">




A 4:3`` picture fills the
        viewing area of a 4:3`` screen,
        but may be stretched or letterboxed when played back on a
        widescreen TV. DVDs using this format are typically
        labelled "full screen."





**Figure&nbsp;B.7.&nbsp;Full-D1
          encoding of 16:9 aspect ratio**


            <img src="images/16_9_dvd.jpg" alt=
            "Full-D1 encoding of 16:9 aspect ratio">




A 16:9`` picture is
        letterboxed when played on a <code class=
        "literal">4:3`` screen, but fills the viewing area of
        a widescreen TV. DVDs using this format are typically
        labelled "widescreen."

        <div class="note" style=
        "margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;">

            Note



DVDs labelled "<a href=
          "#anamorphic_widescreen">anamorphic
          widescreen" or "enhanced for widescreen
          displays" use a direct 16:9``
          encoding of the widescreen picture. If a DVD is labelled
          "widescreen" (but not anamorphic), then the disc probably
          contains a 4:3`` encoding of a
          letterboxed widescreen image&ndash;and consequently,
          wastes 25% or more of its pixels on black letterbox bars.
          Anamorphic widescreen DVDs make better use of their
          available vertical resolution, and are thus superior in
          picture quality to non-anamorphic DVDs. See <a href=
          "http://www.thedigitalbits.com/editorial/bz100298.html"
          target="_top">The ABCs of Anamorphic DVD for a more
          thorough explanation.


Henceforth in this chapter, "widescreen" is synonymous
          with "anamorphic widescreen"; non-anamorphic widescreen
          is ignored completely, as if it never existed.



In these two formats, all letterboxing is done by the
        DVD player (or, in some cases, by the TV). All <code class=
        "literal">720&times;480`` pixels are used optimally,
        with none wasted on black bars. With DVD, consumers can
        choose the aspect ratio that best suits their viewing
        needs.






              <a name=
              "id2501852" id="id2501852">Safe area==





Television sets are not perfect. Most TVs cut off a
        small amount of the picture around the edges, due to
        <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overscan" target=
        "_top">overscan. If there is important imagery or text
        present around the edge, it may not be visible on the
        average TV set. Directors and video producers keep
        important visual elements away from the edges by staying
        within the safe
        area.





**Figure&nbsp;B.8.&nbsp;Safe area of
          90%**


            [images/4_3_safe.jpg]




In doing video production, a good rule of thumb is to
        keep important text inside a 90% "title safe" area, and
        less important elements within a 95% "action safe" area.
        Anything outside 95% is likely to be clipped off by normal
        TV sets.

        <div class="note" style=
        "margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in;">

            Note



If you want to find out your TV's safe area, download
          the <a href="download/safe_area_test_ntsc.mpg" target=
          "_top">NTSC safe area test video or <a href=
          "download/safe_area_test_pal.mpg" target="_top">PAL safe
          area test video. The video is in VCD format; to burn
          it to DVD, first convert it using the <code class=
          "option">-dvd-vcd`` option of <strong class=
          "command"><a href="#tovid" title=
          "tovid">tovid**. This video shows a
          growing green box and a percentage; when the green box
          goes off-screen, make note of the percentage (go
          frame-by-frame if necessary). This percentage is your
          TV's approximate safe area.



