            <a name="glossary" id=
            "glossary">Glossary==





        : <a name="anamorphic_widescreen" id=
        "anamorphic_widescreen">anamorphic widescreen




An anamorphic widescreen DVD is simply one that makes
          good use of vertical resolution. Specifically, it means
          using DVD's 16:9`` aspect
          ratio for all videos having that aspect ratio or greater.
          In the context of filming, anamorphic widescreen is a
          process using special lenses to maximize the use of
          available film exposure area. For more information, see
          the <a href=
          "http://www.thedigitalbits.com/editorial/bz100298.html"
          target="_top">The ABCs of Anamorphic DVD, and the
          <a href=
          "http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anamorphic_widescreen"
          target="_top">Wikipedia article on anamorphic
          widescreen.


        : DVD




Storage technology for optical discs. DVD media can be
          imprinted or recorded with any of several different
          formats. DVD-ROM is the base format, storing files in a
          UDF filesystem; DVD-Video is probably the most common
          application format, and defines how video files are
          stored on the disc and played back in a DVD player.
          DVD-Audio is another increasingly common application
          format. See the <a href=
          "http://www.dvddemystified.com/dvdfaq.html" target=
          "_top">DVD FAQ for more information.


        : HDTV




High definition television


        : <a href=
        "http://www.python.org/" target="_top">Python




Interpreted programming language created by Guido van
          Rossum in 1990. Also the name of the program that
          interprets Python.


        : NTSC




The analog television system used in most of the
          Americas and some parts of East Asia. NTSC is named for
          the National Television System(s) Committee, which
          created the standard. See the <a href=
          "http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/NTSC" target=
          "_top">Wikipedia article on NTSC for more
          information.


        : PAL




The analog television system (more specifically, a
          color encoding) used in most of the world except in most
          of the Americas, and parts of East Asia, the Middle East,
          and Europe. PAL is short for phase-alternating line,
          phase alternation by line or phase alternation line. See
          the <a href="http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/PAL" target=
          "_top">Wikipedia article on PAL for more
          information.


        : SVCD




Super Video Compact Disc (SVCD) is a non-standardized
          format for storing approximately one hour of
          medium-quality video on an ordinary compact disc.
          Although SVCD has not been standardized, SVCD discs are
          playable in most consumer-model DVD players. See <a href=
          "http://www.videohelp.com/svcd/" target="_top">What is
          SVCD? for technical details and a list of
          SVCD-compatible players.


        : VCD




Video Compact Disc (VCD) is a standard format for
          storing slightly more than one hour of low-quality video
          on an ordinary compact disc. VCD follows the White Book
          standard, and is playable in most consumer-model DVD
          players. See <a href="http://www.videohelp.com/vcd/"
          target="_top">What is VCD? for technical details and
          a list of VCD-compatible players.








